(41, 14, 17, 42, 22, 21, 23, 'with the twelve', 'Betrayal at the Table', 'This connection highlights the presence of the twelve disciples at the table, emphasizing the intimate setting where betrayal occurs. Both passages focus on the significance of the gathering and the impending betrayal of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 17, 43, 13, 21, 26, 'with the twelve', 'Betrayal Foretold at Supper', 'This connection highlights the gathering of Jesus with the twelve disciples, as noted in both passages. The mention of ''the twelve'' in Mark sets the stage for the intimate setting where Jesus reveals the betrayal in John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 19, 41, 9, 9, NULL, 'Betrayal by a close friend', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal by a familiar friend. Both passages mention a betrayal involving someone who shared a meal, emphasizing the deep sense of trust broken in such an act.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 43, 6, 47, 47, 'Verily I say unto you', 'Connection of Betrayal and Belief', 'This connection highlights the contrast between betrayal and belief. In Mark, the act of betrayal is emphasized, while in John, belief leads to everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 43, 6, 70, 70, 'one of you which eateth with me', 'Betrayal and Deception Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of betrayal among Jesus'' chosen disciples. In Mark, Jesus reveals that one of those eating with him will betray him, while in John, he identifies one of the twelve as a devil, indicating deceit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 40, 5, 18, 18, NULL, 'Betrayal and Fulfillment of Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfillment in both passages. In Mark, the betrayal signifies a pivotal moment leading to the fulfillment of Jesus'' mission, while in Matthew, the emphasis on the law''s permanence until all is fulfilled underscores the importance of every detail in God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 40, 6, 2, 2, 'Verily I say unto you', 'Betrayal and Hypocrisy Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and hypocrisy. Both passages emphasize the idea of individuals acting deceitfully while in the presence of others, whether through betrayal at a meal or through performing good deeds for public recognition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 41, 3, 28, 28, NULL, 'Forgiveness and Betrayal Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal in Mark 14:18, where one of Jesus'' closest followers will betray him, contrasting with the promise of forgiveness in Mark 3:28. Both passages emphasize the gravity of sin and the possibility of redemption, suggesting a complex relationship between human actions and divine forgiveness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 18, 41, 6, 11, 11, 'Verily I say unto you', 'Betrayal and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal leading to judgment. In both passages, the actions of individuals result in severe consequences, emphasizing accountability for one''s choices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 19, 40, 26, 22, 22, 'Is it I?', 'Sorrowful Inquiry of Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' sorrow and their questioning of their own loyalty to Jesus. The repeated phrase ''Is it I?'' highlights their concern about betrayal in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 19, 42, 22, 21, 23, 'Is it I?', 'Betrayal Inquiry Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' sorrow and inquiry about betrayal. They reflect a shared moment of confusion and concern among the disciples regarding who would betray Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 19, 43, 13, 22, 22, 'Is it I?', 'Disciples'' Doubt and Sorrow', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' uncertainty and sorrow regarding betrayal. In Mark, they ask, ''Is it I?'' while in John, they are ''doubting of whom he spake.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 43, 13, 26, 26, 'dippeth with me in the dish', 'Connection of Betrayal in Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the act of dipping, which signifies the betrayal of Judas Iscariot. In Mark, Jesus identifies the betrayer as one of the twelve who dips with him, while John specifies that Jesus gives the sop to Judas after dipping.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 40, 26, 23, 23, 'dippeth with me in the dish', 'Betrayal by One of Twelve', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of the betrayer as one of the twelve disciples who shares a meal with Jesus. The act of dipping in the dish serves as a direct link between the two accounts, highlighting the intimate nature of the betrayal.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 40, 26, 47, 47, 'one of the twelve', 'Connection of Judas'' Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize Judas as ''one of the twelve,'' highlighting his role in the betrayal of Jesus. The first passage identifies Judas'' presence at the Last Supper, while the second depicts his arrival with a multitude to arrest Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 41, 14, 43, 43, 'one of the twelve', 'Betrayal by One of the Twelve', 'This connection highlights the identity of Judas as one of the twelve disciples, linking his betrayal in the first passage to his arrival with a multitude in the second. Both passages emphasize the significance of Judas''s role in the events leading to Jesus''s arrest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 42, 22, 47, 47, 'one of the twelve', 'Connection of Betrayal by Judas', 'Both passages emphasize Judas as one of the twelve disciples, highlighting his role in the betrayal of Jesus. The act of dipping in the dish in Mark foreshadows the subsequent betrayal with a kiss in Luke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 20, 43, 6, 71, 71, 'one of the twelve', 'Connection of Betrayal by Judas', 'Both passages emphasize Judas Iscariot as one of the twelve disciples who betrays Jesus. Mark identifies him through the act of dipping in the dish, while John explicitly names him as the betrayer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 23, 53, 1, 12, 'the Son of man is betrayed', 'Betrayal and Suffering Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and suffering in both passages. Mark 14:21 speaks of the betrayal of the Son of Man, while Isaiah 53 describes the suffering servant who bears the iniquities of others, emphasizing the consequences of betrayal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 40, 26, 24, 25, 'woe to that man by whom the Son of man is betrayed', 'Connection of Betrayal and Woe', 'Both passages emphasize the betrayal of the Son of man and the resulting woe for the betrayer. The phrase ''woe to that man by whom the Son of man is betrayed'' appears in both, highlighting the gravity of the act.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 1, 3, 15, 15, 'woe to that man by whom the Son of man is betrayed', 'Betrayal and Enmity Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and its consequences. In Mark, the betrayal of the Son of man leads to dire consequences, while Genesis introduces enmity between the serpent and the woman''s seed, suggesting conflict stemming from betrayal.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 27, 9, 24, 24, 'woe to that man by whom the Son of man is betrayed', 'Connection of Betrayal and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal in Mark 14:21, where the fate of the betrayer is emphasized, paralleling the prophetic timeline in Daniel 9:24 that anticipates the resolution of sin and transgression. Both passages underscore the seriousness of actions leading to reconciliation and righteousness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 38, 13, 7, 7, 'the Son of man is betrayed', 'Betrayal and Shepherd Motif', 'Both passages emphasize the betrayal of a shepherd figure. Mark refers to the Son of man being betrayed, while Zechariah speaks of smiting the shepherd, leading to the scattering of the sheep.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 40, 18, 6, 7, 'woe to that man', 'Woes for Betrayers and Offenders', 'Both passages emphasize the severe consequences for those who lead others into betrayal or offense. The repeated use of ''woe'' highlights the gravity of these actions and their impact on both the betrayer and the innocent.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 21, 43, 19, 28, 28, 'the Son of man is betrayed', 'Connection of Betrayal and Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and its consequences. In Mark, the betrayal of the Son of man is foreshadowed, while in John, Jesus'' awareness of fulfilling scripture underscores the inevitability of that betrayal.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
